At least two people have been seriously injured after an attacker went on a rampage at a shopping centre in Sweden. Police say they detained one person on the spot following the apparent knife attack in Vasteras. Local media suggested the number of people hurt may be higher and that some of the injuries could be life-threatening. Officers said in a statement that a sharp object had been used but did not provide further detail. Swedish daily Aftonbladet, citing unnamed sources, reported that the victims were stabbed with a knife. The paper said the incident was being treated as attempted murder but the motive behind the attack was unclear. Police said the attack took place in the central part of Vasteras, a town about 90 kilometres (56 miles) west of Stockholm. Spokesman Magnus Jansson Klarin explained that police do not believe anyone else was involved, The Mirror reported. He said: ‘We receive several calls in a short time that there has been several [people] injured. ‘We can not rule out that more people have been injured. ‘[The area] has been blocked off and the police have a large presence at the [scene].’ There have been a series of stabbings in Sweden in recent times, notably a string of incidents at schools. Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page. MORE : Dozens injured in Sweden after Quran burning sparks days of riots